{{double image|right|William Walton.jpg|125|Jock Wallace.jpg|125|Managers [[William Wilton]] and [[Jock Wallace]] led [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] to a total of ten league championships.}}
The '''Scottish football champions''' are the winners of the highest league in [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]], namely the [[Scottish Football League]] from 1890 until 1998 and the [[Scottish Premier League]] thereafter.

The Scottish Football League was established in 1890, initially as an amateur league until professionalism in Scottish football was  legalised in 1893.<ref name="Davies158">{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Hunter |title=Boots, Balls and Haircuts: An Illustrated History of Football from Then to Now |isbn=1-8440-3261-2 |date=2003 |publisher=Cassell Illustrated |pages=p39}}</ref>  At the end of the [[1890-91 in Scottish football|1890&ndash;91]] season [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] finished level on points at the top of the table.  The rules in force at the time required that the teams contest a play-off match for the championship, which finished in a 2&ndash;2 draw, and the first ever championship was thus shared between two clubs, the only occasion on which this has happened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotchamp.html|title=Scotland &ndash; List of Champions|publisher=RSSSF|accessdate=2008-03-05|date=2007-08-22}}</ref>  In 1893 a Second Division was formed, with the existing single division renamed the First Division.  Although there were several short spells when a third division was created, the two-division structure remained largely in place until 1975, when a major re-organisation of the league led to a new three-tier set-up and the creation of a new [[Scottish Football League Premier Division|Premier Division]] at the highest level.  The league continued during the [[First World War]] but was suspended during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotall.html|title=Scotland &ndash; List of Divisional Movements|publisher=RSSSF|accessdate=2008-03-05|date=2007-01-03}}</ref>    In 1998, the teams then in the Premier Division broke away to form the Scottish Premier League, which supplanted the Premier Division as the highest level of football in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotprem.premiumtv.co.uk/page/History/0,,10002,00.html|title=History|publisher=Scottish Premier League|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref> 

Throughout its existence the championship of Scottish football has been dominated by two [[Glasgow]] clubs, [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], the so-called "[[Old Firm]]", who have claimed 51 and 41 league titles respectively as of 2007.  No other club has won the title on more than four occasions, with the most recent club outside the Old Firm to win the title being [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in the [[1984-85 in Scottish football|1984&ndash;85]] season.  Each of the Old Firm clubs has at one time managed a run of nine consecutive championships, Celtic from 1966 to 1974 and Rangers from 1989 to 1997.  The Old Firm's longest period of unbroken dominance came between 1904 and 1931 when the two clubs between them won 27 consecutive titles.  
Each of the two clubs has also claimed Scotland's version of [[The Double]] on many occasions, by winning the league and the [[Scottish Cup]] in the same season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celticfc.net/home/about/briefHistory.aspx|title=Brief history|publisher=Celtic F.C.|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref>  Rangers have won the most Doubles with seventeen as of 2007, more than any other club in the world apart from [[Northern Ireland]]'s [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/doublerec.html|title=Doing the Double!|publisher=RSSSF|accessdate=2008-03-05|date=2008-02-28}}</ref>  Each club has also won a Double and added the [[Scottish League Cup]] to make it a [[The Treble|Treble]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/HistoryDetail/0,,5~456,00.html|title=1946&ndash;1970 An Historic Treble|publisher=Rangers F.C.|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref>  In the [[1966-67 in Scottish football|1966&ndash;67]] season Celtic took all three domestic trophies and also won the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] to complete the only [[The Quadruple|Quadruple]] to date.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/theknowledge/story/0,,2022367,00.html|title=The sulkiest football walk-offs ever|work=The Guardian|date=2007-02-28|author=James Dart, Paolo Bandini and Sean Armstrong|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref>

